The Modern browsers continuously introduce new CSS features but not every browser supports every CSS property. The JavaScript provides multiple ways to detect CSS property support allowing developers to build more reliable and browser compatible web applications.
In this article, you’ll learn different methods to check if a CSS property is supported in the browser using JavaScript along with practical examples.
Why Check CSS Property Support?
Checking CSS property support offers several advantages when developing modern websites.

• Prevents layout and styling issues in unsupported browsers.

• Improves cross-browser compatibility.

• Helps implement progressive enhancement.
Method 1: Using CSS.supports()
The CSS.supports() method is the recommended and most reliable way to determine whether a browser supports a CSS property-value pair. It returns true if the property is supported & false otherwise.
if (CSS.supports("display", "grid")) {
console.log("CSS Grid is supported.");
} else {
console.log("CSS Grid is not supported.");
}Output :
CSS Grid is supported.
Method 2: Using the style Object
Every HTML element has a style object containing the CSS properties recognized by the browser. We can check whether a property exists using the in operator.
const div = document.createElement("div");
if ("backdropFilter" in div.style) {
console.log("Backdrop Filter is supported.");
} else {
console.log("Backdrop Filter is not supported.");
}Output :
Backdrop Filter is supported.
Method 3: Creating a Reusable Function
A reusable function simplifies checking different CSS properties throughout your application.
function isCSSPropertySupported(property) {
const element = document.createElement("div");
return property in element.style;
}
console.log(isCSSPropertySupported("borderRadius"));
console.log(isCSSPropertySupported("aspectRatio"));
console.log(isCSSPropertySupported("fakeProperty"));Output :
true
true
false
Method 4: Checking Multiple CSS Properties
You may want to verify support for several CSS properties before enabling advanced UI features.
const properties = [
"gridTemplateColumns",
"backdropFilter",
"aspectRatio",
"containerType"
];
const element = document.createElement("div");
properties.forEach(property => {
console.log(property, property in element.style);
});Output :
gridTemplateColumns true
backdropFilter true
aspectRatio true
containerType true.
Complete Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>CSS Property Support Checker</title>
</head>
<body>
<button onclick="checkSupport()">
Check CSS Support
</button>
<p id="result"></p>
<script>
function checkSupport() {
const property = "backdropFilter";
const element = document.createElement("div");
const supported = property in element.style;
document.getElementById("result").textContent =
supported
? property + " is supported."
: property + " is not supported.";
}
</script>
</body>
</html>Output :
backdropFilter is supported.
Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)
1. What is the best way to check CSS property support?
The CSS.supports() method is the recommended approach because it validates both the CSS property and its value. It is standardized & supported in all modern browsers.
2. What does CSS.supports() return?
It returns a Boolean value. A return value of true indicates that the browser supports the specified property-value pair while false indicates that it does not.
3. Can I check only the CSS property without specifying a value?
Yes. We can use the style object & the in operator to determine whether a CSS property exists. This method only checks property recognition not whether a specific value is supported.
4. Does feature detection work better than browser detection?
Yes. Feature detection verifies whether a browser actually supports a CSS feature whereas browser detection relies on browser names or versions.
5. Can I check support for new CSS features like Container Queries?
Yes. We can use CSS.supports() or the style object to detect support for modern CSS properties such as container-type or aspect-ratio.
6. Is CSS.supports() available in all browsers?
It is supported in all modern browsers including Chrome, Firefox, Edge & Safari.
Conclusion
Checking CSS property support in JavaScript helps create robust & browser-compatible web applications. The CSS.supports() method is the preferred solution because it accurately verifies both CSS properties & values. Alternatively, the style object provides a simple way to detect property existence while vendor-prefixed checks help maintain compatibility with older browsers. By using feature detection instead of browser detection developers can build responsive & future-proof websites with confidence.
